TY  - JOUR
T1  - Alternate Approaches to Integrating Longitudinal Case Studies
AU  - McPhee, Robert D.
Y1  - 1990/11/01
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.1.4.393
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.1.4.393
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 393
EP  - 405
VL  - 1
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In dealing with a large set of longitudinal case studies, researchers often assume that they can and should seek a single set of variables and explanatory theory to deal similarly with all the cases. This paper describes three approaches to the problems of cross-case integration and comparison. It also describes a set of comparative methods that can be used to diagnose case-study data-sets, to see which integrative approach is best.
AB  - In dealing with a large set of longitudinal case studies, researchers often assume that they can and should seek a single set of variables and explanatory theory to deal similarly with all the cases. This paper describes three approaches to the problems of cross-case integration and comparison. It also describes a set of comparative methods that can be used to diagnose case-study data-sets, to see which integrative approach is best.
